Graduate Employment Trajectory: At Graduation vs. Three Years Later

Code 
# Read in data file
merge = pd.read_excel("./BIOT_Initial_Three_Year_Outcome.xlsx")
merge = merge[merge['EmploymentStatus_Three_year'].notna()]

# filter out the students who have already graduated for three years

# Calculate the employment status distribution
status_counts_initial = merge['EmploymentStatus_Initial'].value_counts(normalize=True)
status_counts_3year = merge['EmploymentStatus_Three_year'].value_counts(normalize=True)

# Custom colors that work well with Georgetown's style
colors = {
    'Employed': '#012169', 
    'Unknown': '#1E3A8A', 
    'Pursuing Advanced Degree': '#BBBCBC', 
    'Seeking Opportunities': '#D6D2C4' 
}
# Create donut charts with improved text positioning and clear labels
fig = make_subplots(rows=1, cols=2, specs=[[{'type': 'domain'}, {'type': 'domain'}]])

# Initial employment status donut chart - with improved text positioning and labels
fig.add_trace(go.Pie(
    labels=status_counts_initial.index,
    values=status_counts_initial.values,
    hole=0.5, 
    textinfo='label+percent',  # Show both label and percentage inside
    textposition='outside',
    marker_colors=[colors.get(status, '#A0A0A0') for status in status_counts_initial.index],
    insidetextorientation='radial', 
    insidetextfont=dict(size=10), 
    textfont=dict(size=10),   
    pull=[0.03, 0.03, 0.03, 0.03],  
    automargin=True
), 1, 1)

# Three-year employment status donut chart - with improved text positioning and labels
fig.add_trace(go.Pie(
    labels=status_counts_3year.index,
    values=status_counts_3year.values,
    hole=0.5, 
    textinfo='label+percent',  # Show both label and percentage inside
    textposition='outside',
    marker_colors=[colors.get(status, '#A0A0A0') for status in status_counts_3year.index],
    insidetextorientation='radial', 
    insidetextfont=dict(size=10),   
    textfont=dict(size=10), 
    pull=[0.03, 0.03, 0.03, 0.03],  
    automargin=True
), 1, 2)

# Update layout
fig.update_layout(
    title=dict(
        text="<b>Employment Status Comparison: At Graduation vs. Three Years Later</b>",
        x=0.5,
        xanchor="center",
        font=dict(size=18)
    ),
    height=600,
    width=900,
    showlegend=True,
    legend=dict(
        orientation="v",  
        x=1.05,           
        y=0.5,             
        xanchor="left",
        yanchor="middle"
    ),
    margin=dict(t=80, b=100, l=80, r=80),
    annotations=[
        dict(text="*Data reflects 452 BIOT graduates.", x=0.5, y=-0.15,  # place below the charts
            xanchor="center", showarrow=False, font=dict(size=10, color="gray"),align="center"),
        # Chart labels below each donut
        dict(text="At Graduation", x=0.20, y=0, xanchor="center", showarrow=False, font_size=16),
        dict(text="Three Years Later", x=0.80, y=0, xanchor="center", showarrow=False, font_size=16)
    ]
)

pio.write_image(fig, "employment_status_comparison.png")
#fig.write_image("employment_status_comparison.png")

This data tracks the employment status of 452 Biotechnology graduates at graduation and again three years later.

While only 59% were employed right after graduation, the fact that 95% were working three years later shows strong long-term career outcomes from the program.

Employment Status Comparison: Bar Chart

A side-by-side comparison of the counts in each employment status category.

Code 
# Filter out rows where either employment status is NaN
status_comparison = merge[
    (merge['EmploymentStatus_Three_year'].notna()) & 
    (merge['EmploymentStatus_Initial'].notna())
]

# Define a consistent order
status_order = ['Employed', 'Pursuing Advanced Degree', 'Seeking Opportunities', 'Unknown']

# Calculate the counts
initial_counts = status_comparison['EmploymentStatus_Initial'].value_counts().reindex(status_order, fill_value=0)
three_year_counts = status_comparison['EmploymentStatus_Three_year'].value_counts().reindex(status_order, fill_value=0)

# Create comparison data frame
counts_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'Initial': initial_counts,
    'Three Years': three_year_counts
})

# Create simple bar chart
fig = go.Figure()

# Add bars for initial counts
fig.add_trace(go.Bar(
    x=counts_df.index,
    y=counts_df['Initial'],
    name='Initial Outcome',
    text=counts_df['Initial'],
    textposition='auto',
    marker_color='#012169',
))

# Add bars for three-year counts
fig.add_trace(go.Bar(
    x=counts_df.index,
    y=counts_df['Three Years'],
    name='Three Years After Graduation',
    text=counts_df['Three Years'],
    textposition='auto',
    marker_color='#BBBCBC',
))

# Simple layout
fig.update_layout(
    title=dict(
    text='Comparison of Employment Status Counts',
    x=0.5,
    xanchor='center',
    font=dict(size=18)
    ),
    xaxis_title='Employment Status',
    yaxis_title='Number of Students',
    barmode='group',
    height=500,
    width=800
)

pio.write_image(fig, "employment_status_comparison_bar_chart.png")

Employment nearly doubled from graduation to three years later (265 → 430), while the number of unknown outcomes dropped to near zero — showing both strong career progression and better follow-up data quality.

# Calculate counts and percentages
initial_status_counts = merge['EmploymentStatus_Initial'].value_counts()

Industry Distribution for Employed Graduates

Code 
from plotly.subplots import make_subplots
import plotly.graph_objects as go
import plotly.express as px

# Filter industry distributions
employed_industry_initial = merge[merge['EmploymentStatus_Initial'] == 'Employed']['FirstIndustry'].value_counts(normalize=True)
employed_industry_3year = merge[merge['EmploymentStatus_Three_year'] == 'Employed']['Industry'].value_counts(normalize=True)

# Create side-by-side donut charts
fig = make_subplots(
    rows=1, cols=2,
    specs=[[{'type': 'domain'}, {'type': 'domain'}]],
    subplot_titles=["Initial Industry Distribution", "Three-Year Industry Distribution"]
)

# Define a qualitative color palette
industry_colors = px.colors.qualitative.Bold

# Initial industry distribution donut
fig.add_trace(go.Pie(
    labels=employed_industry_initial.index,
    values=employed_industry_initial.values,
    hole=0.5,
    textinfo='label+percent',
    textposition='inside',
    insidetextorientation='radial',
    insidetextfont=dict(size=9),
    marker_colors=industry_colors[:len(employed_industry_initial)],
    pull=[0.03] * len(employed_industry_initial)
), 1, 1)

# Three-year industry distribution donut
fig.add_trace(go.Pie(
    labels=employed_industry_3year.index,
    values=employed_industry_3year.values,
    hole=0.5,
    textinfo='label+percent',
    textposition='inside',
    insidetextorientation='radial',
    insidetextfont=dict(size=9),
    marker_colors=industry_colors[:len(employed_industry_3year)],
    pull=[0.03] * len(employed_industry_3year)
), 1, 2)

fig.update_layout(
    title=dict(
        text="<b>Industry Distribution of Employed Graduates</b>",
        x=0.5,
        xanchor='center',
        font=dict(size=18),
        y=0.98  
    ),
    height=600,
    width=1000,
    showlegend=True,
    legend=dict(
        orientation="v",
        y=0.5,
        x=1.05,
        xanchor="left"
    ),
    margin=dict(t=120, b=50, l=50, r=150)  
)

pio.write_image(fig, "industry_distribution.png")

Initially, employed graduates entered a wide range of industries, with BioPharma accounting for 39.4% of roles. Three years later, BioPharma dominates at 69.5%, indicating a strong long-term alignment between graduate skillsets and the needs of that industry. This shift suggests that biotech students are ultimately landing in the field they were trained for and likely intended to enter, while early roles in sectors like Consulting and Business may serve as stepping stones or transitional paths.

Sector & Industry Comparison for Initially and Three-Year Employed Graduates

Code 
# Filter for students employed at both time points
employed_df = merge[(merge['EmploymentStatus_Three_year'] == 'Employed') & 
                    (merge['EmploymentStatus_Initial'] == 'Employed')]

# Count the sectors for initial and 3-year outcomes
sector_counts_initial = employed_df['FirstSector'].value_counts()
sector_counts_three_years = employed_df['Sector'].value_counts()

# Find all unique sectors across both time points
all_sectors = list(set(sector_counts_initial.index) | set(sector_counts_three_years.index))

# Create a DataFrame from the counts with consistent ordering
sector_comparison = pd.DataFrame({
    'Initial': sector_counts_initial.reindex(all_sectors, fill_value=0),
    'Three Years': sector_counts_three_years.reindex(all_sectors, fill_value=0)
})

# Sort by the sum of counts (both initial and three years)
sector_comparison['Total'] = sector_comparison['Initial'] + sector_comparison['Three Years']
sector_comparison = sector_comparison.sort_values('Total', ascending=False).drop('Total', axis=1)

# Create horizontal bar chart with Plotly
fig = go.Figure()

# Add bars for initial counts
fig.add_trace(go.Bar(
    y=sector_comparison.index,
    x=sector_comparison['Initial'],
    name='Initial Employment',
    text=sector_comparison['Initial'].astype(int),
    textposition='auto',
    marker_color='#012169',
    orientation='h',
))

# Add bars for three-year counts
fig.add_trace(go.Bar(
    y=sector_comparison.index,
    x=sector_comparison['Three Years'],
    name='Three Years Later',
    text=sector_comparison['Three Years'].astype(int),
    textposition='auto',
    marker_color='#BBBCBC',
    orientation='h',
))

# Update layout
fig.update_layout(
    title=dict(
        text="<b>Sector Comparison for Employed Individuals Initially and After 3 Years</b>",
        x=0.5,
        xanchor='center',
        font=dict(size=18),
        y=0.98  
    ),
    xaxis_title='Number of Students',
    yaxis_title='Sector',
    barmode='group',
    height=500,
    width=800,
    margin=dict(l=150, r=20, t=80, b=50)  # Add more left margin for sector labels
)

pio.write_image(fig, "sector_comparison.png")

While most sectors remained stable over time, Research saw a notable increase in graduate representation (129 → 144), reinforcing its role as a long-term destination aligned with the academic and scientific training students receive. Meanwhile, declines in Consulting (24 → 6) and Regulatory Affairs (22 → 11) suggest these roles may serve as launchpads into more specialized functions as graduates build experience.

Notably, Finance and Administration and Marketing and Communications remained steady across both timelines, indicating they offer consistent career opportunities for students pursuing alternative paths within the biotech ecosystem — especially those with dual interests in science and business.

Employment Status by Citizenship

Code 
# Create a stacked bar chart comparing employment status by citizenship
# Initial status
citizenship_initial = pd.crosstab(
    merge['Citizenship Description'], 
    merge['EmploymentStatus_Initial'],
    normalize='index'
) * 100

# Three-year status
citizenship_three_year = pd.crosstab(
    merge['Citizenship Description'], 
    merge['EmploymentStatus_Three_year'],
    normalize='index'
) * 100

# Create subplots
fig = make_subplots(
    rows=1, cols=2,
    subplot_titles=["Initial Employment Status by Citizenship", 
                    "Three-Year Employment Status by Citizenship"],
    shared_yaxes=True
)

# Add traces for initial status
for status in citizenship_initial.columns:
    fig.add_trace(
        go.Bar(
            x=citizenship_initial.index,
            y=citizenship_initial[status],
            name=status,
            marker_color=colors.get(status, '#A0A0A0'),
            text=[f"{val:.1f}%" for val in citizenship_initial[status]],
            textposition='inside',
        ),
        row=1, col=1
    )

# Add traces for three-year status
for status in citizenship_three_year.columns:
    fig.add_trace(
        go.Bar(
            x=citizenship_three_year.index,
            y=citizenship_three_year[status],
            name=status,
            marker_color=colors.get(status, '#A0A0A0'),
            text=[f"{val:.1f}%" for val in citizenship_three_year[status]],
            textposition='inside',
            showlegend=False,  # Don't duplicate legend items
        ),
        row=1, col=2
    )

# Update layout
fig.update_layout(
    barmode='stack',
    title=dict(
        text="<b>Employment Status by Citizenship: Initial vs. Three Years Later</b>",
        x=0.5,
        xanchor='center',
        font=dict(size=18)
    ),
    yaxis_title="Percentage",
    height=500,
    width=900,
    legend=dict(
        orientation="h",
        y=-0.25,  # push legend below the plot
        x=0.5,
        xanchor="center"
    ),
    margin=dict(t=100, b=100, l=50, r=50)  # more top/bottom padding
)

pio.write_image(fig, "employment_by_citizenship.png")
